Security groups versus network A-C-Ls.

A security group is a virtual firewall attached to an E-N-I, the network interface on an instance, a load balancer, an R-D-S database, a V-P-C Lambda, anything with an I-P in your V-P-C. Four properties define it. It's stateful: if you allow inbound on port four-forty-three, the return traffic is allowed automatically, with no matching outbound rule. It's allow-only: there's no deny, and everything you don't permit is implicitly denied. Multiple security groups per E-N-I combine additively: if any one allows the traffic, it's allowed. And a rule can reference another security group as its source; "allow port eighty-eighty from the A-L-B's security group" tracks instances automatically as they scale, which is far better than a fixed I-P range.

A network A-C-L sits one layer up, at the subnet boundary, and has inverted properties. It's stateless: return traffic is not automatically allowed. It supports both allow and deny rules. And it evaluates them in order, first match wins. The default N-A-C-L allows everything; a custom N-A-C-L denies everything until you add rules.

The stateless property is the classic trap. Because responses aren't auto-allowed, you must permit both directions, and a response comes back on an ephemeral port, which on Linux is one-thousand-twenty-four to sixty-five-thousand-five-thirty-five. Allow inbound four-forty-three but forget outbound on the ephemeral range, and the handshake completes and then hangs. The rule of thumb: security groups do ninety-nine percent of the work; reach for a N-A-C-L only to deny something, like an I-P block, at the subnet edge.
